{"id":"1910.06063","submitter":"Abinash Tripathy Dr.","authors":"Chandantaru Dey Modak, Arvind Kumar, Abinash Tripathy and Prosenjit\n  Sen","title":"Drop Impact Printing","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Nat Commun 11, 4327 (2020)","doi":"10.1038/s41467-020-18103-6","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.app-ph cond-mat.soft physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Hydrodynamic collapse of a central air-cavity during the recoil phase of\ndroplet impact on a superhydrophobic sieve leads to satellite-free generation\nof a single droplet through the sieve. Two modes of cavity formation and\ndroplet ejection was observed and explained. The volume of the generated\ndroplet scales with the pore size. Based on this phenomenon, we propose a new\ndrop-on-demand printing technique. Despite significant advancements in inkjet\ntechnology, enhancement in mass-loading and particle-size have been limited due\nto clogging of the printhead nozzle. By replacing the nozzle with a sieve, we\ndemonstrate printing of nanoparticle suspension with 71% mass-loading.\nComparatively large particles of 20 micrometer diameter were dispensed in\ndroplets of 80 micrometer diameter. Printing was performed for surface tension\nas low as 32 mNm-1 and viscosity as high as 33 mPa-s. In comparison to existing\ntechniques, this new way of printing is widely accessible as it is\nsignificantly simple and economical.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 17 Sep 2019 16:16:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-08-31"}
